<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Pinus contorta </i>ssp. <i>murrayana </i>is a conifer that attains a height of 30 m and age of over 600 years. Cone crops are heavy about every 3 years. Seeds are wind dispersed and fall up to 60 m from source trees. Seeds are about 75% viable and remain viable for up to 15 years. High germination occurs in locations with high light and soils with little or no duff. Local regeneration may occur as gaps are caused by tree fall. Trees are moderately shade tolerant. Many stands have uneven-aged structure (Cope 1993c, Griffin and Critchfield 1972 Lotan and Critchfield 1990, Parker 1986).<br/>
<br/>
<i>Pinus contorta </i>includes four subspecies that have different ecologies (Lotan and Critchfield 1990), so we treated them in separate alliances: ssp. <i>contorta </i>grows along the coastline of northern California; ssp. <i>bolanderi </i>is a regular component of the <i>Hesperocyparis pigmaea </i>alliance; ssp. <i>latifolia </i>is thought to grow outside California (it might be on serpentine substrates in the northern Klamath Mountains; see <i>Pinus contorta </i>ssp. <i>contorta </i>alliance); and ssp. <i>murrayana </i>grows at higher elevations in California’s mountains. <br/>
<br/>
<i>Pinus contorta </i>ssp. <i>murrayana </i>grows in a variety of site conditions, including cold air drainages, stream banks, lakeshores, wet meadows, and dry, upland settings. Stands are most common and extensive in the Sierra Nevada. Montane stands are associated with moist meadow and lake margins; subalpine stands occupy upland settings on glaciated surfaces and till with skeletal soils (Fites-Kaufman et al. 2007). </div>
</div>

    
	
	
