<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Fire Characteristics</h4>
	<div class="text"><i>Pinus contorta </i>ssp. <i>murrayana </i>trees are fire sensitive because of shallow roots and thin bark. Fires of moderate to high severity remove existing vegetation and prepare an ideal seedbed for seedling establishment for this post-fire colonizer. This pine typically establishes from wind-dispersed seed after stand-replacing fires; trees also establish between fires, creating even-aged stands (Cope 1993c).

Fire return intervals vary. On the west side of the Cascades and Sierra Nevada, stand-replacing events are several hundred years apart (Skinner and Taylor 2006, van Wagtendonk and Fites-Kaufman 2007). Fires are usually intense and extensive, and they are related especially to insect attacks and declining vigor in older stands (Cope 1993c).</div>
	<table class="zebraStripe">
		
		<tr>
			<td class="key">Fire return interval</td>
			<td>Medium to long (100+ years for large stand-replacing fires, 20-30 years for surface fires)
				
			</td>
		</tr>
		
		<tr>
			<td class="key">Seasonality</td>
			<td>Late summer (short)
				
			</td>
		</tr>
		
