		</tr>
		
	</table>
</div>



    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Klamath Mountains</b> (M261Ad-e, Ag, Aj, An-q, At). Stands occur in all higher mountain ranges in the section. They are mostly associated with glacial basins and lakes (Sawyer 2007).</li>
        
            <li><b>Modoc Plateau</b> (M261Gf). Stands are associated with depressions that are cold and seasonally saturated (Fites-Kaufman 2007). Stands are common in the northern Warner Mountains, some with an understory of <i>Vaccinium scoparium.</i></li>
        
            <li><b>Mono</b> (341Dd, Dj, Dl). Stands are extensive at higher elevations in upland settings, including those at Indiana Summit and Sentinel Meadow RNAs (Cheng 2004, Thorne et al. 2007). Individuals, groves, and a single valley-bottom stand occur in the White Mountains (Griffin and Critchfield 1972).</li>
        
            <li><b>Sierra Nevada</b> (M261Ea-h, Ej-q, Et-u). Stands are described for Bell Meadow, Grass Lake, Harvey Monroe Hall, Last Chance, Mount Pleasant, Mud Lake, and W. B. Critchfield RNAs; for the Teakettle Creek study area (Cheng 2004), for Yosemite National Park (Keeler-Wolf et al. 2003b); and generally in the section (Fites-Kaufman 2007, Potter 1994, 1998, 2005).</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern California Mountains and Valleys</b> (M262Be, Bh, Bm). Stands occur in the San Gabriel, San Bernardino, and San Jacinto mountains (Hanes 1976, Minnich 1976, 2007, Klein and Evens 2005) at subalpine elevations in both upland and moist, lowlying settings.</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern Cascades</b> (M261Dd, Df-g, Di-j, Dl-m). Stands are associated with depressions that are cold and seasonally saturated (Fites-Kaufman 2007).</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> Stand-replacing fires are related to insect attacks, particularly by the lodgepine needleminer (<i>Coleotechnites milleri</i>) and mountain pine beetle (<i>Dendroctonus ponderosae</i>), and to high fuel loading in old stands (Keeley 1981, Parker 1986, Wood et al. 2003). Issues surrounding the “invasion” of <i>Pinus contorta </i>ssp<i>. murrayana </i>into subalpine meadows have raised concerns with managers because of uncertainty regarding whether these shifts are natural or human mediated. </div>
</div>

    

    

